<TITLE> Chinese bank gives Kenya $20 mln for cheap housing </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NAIROBI, Dec 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - China Development Bank will provide $20 million in development credit to build low-cost housing and improve education and health care in Kenya, the bank's top official in Africa said on Thursday. More than half the money will go towards construction of low- and medium-income houses in the east African country, which has a government target of building 150,000 new units each year. "We want to improve the livelihoods of people in Kenya by focusing on low-income houses, education and health care," said Zhu Qingdong, general director of the Africa Project Development Team. The $20 million is the first line of credit and will be repaid in 15 years at concessionary rates that are yet to be worked out. More lines are expected. Finance Minister Amos Kimunya defended the government against charges it is favouring Chinese companies by awarding them lucrative contracts. "We are in a global economy and Kenya is privileged to partner with China, the fastest growing economy in the world," he said at the signing of the agreement at the ministry. He said China's Overseas Development Assistance to Kenya stands at 14.75 billion Kenya shillings ($230.5 million). China has become one of the biggest investors in Africa, offering cheap loans for development projects that often are carried out by Chinese companies. Chinese-funded work in East Africa's biggest economy includes rehabilitation of roads, modernization of electricity distribution and a rural telecommunications proje
